1. A – Atomicity (All or Nothing)

A transaction must happen completely or not at all.

👉 Example:
You transfer ₹1000 from A to B:

Debit A (₹1000)
Credit B (₹1000)

If system crashes after debit but before credit → entire transaction is rolled back.

✔ Either both steps happen
✔ Or nothing happens

2. C – Consistency (Valid Data Only)

Database must always move from one valid state to another valid state.

👉 Rules (constraints) must never break:

Balance cannot become negative (if rule exists)
Foreign key rules must be followed

✔ Data always remains correct according to rules

3. I – Isolation (No Interference)

Multiple transactions running at the same time should not affect each other.

👉 Example:
Two users trying to book the last train ticket:

Only one should succeed
Other should not see half-updated data

✔ Each transaction behaves like it is running alone

4. D – Durability (Permanent after Save)

Once a transaction is completed, the data is permanently saved.

👉 Even if:

Power fails
System crashes

✔ Data will still be there after restart

🔥 Simple Memory Trick:

A C I D

A = All or nothing


ACID Properties
1. Atomicity (All or Nothing)
🎤 Definition:

"Atomicity ensures that a transaction is executed completely or not executed at all. If any part of the transaction fails, the entire transaction is rolled back."

Example:
Transferring ₹1000 from Account A to Account B.

Debit from A ✅
Credit to B ❌ (fails)

➡️ Entire transaction is rolled back.

2. Consistency (Valid State)
🎤 Definition:

"Consistency ensures that a transaction takes the database from one valid state to another valid state while maintaining all database rules and constraints."

Example:
After transferring money:

Total balance remains correct.
No foreign key or other constraint is violated.
3. Isolation (No Interference)
🎤 Definition:

"Isolation ensures that multiple transactions executing at the same time do not interfere with each other. Each transaction behaves as if it is running independently."

Example:
Two users try to book the last seat.

One transaction commits.
The other waits, fails, or is rolled back.
4. Durability (Permanent Save)
🎤 Definition:

"Durability ensures that once a transaction is committed, the changes are permanently saved in the database, even if the system crashes or power fails."

Example:
You transfer money successfully.
Immediately after that, the server crashes.

➡️ After restart, the transfer is still saved because it was already committed.

🔥 One-line Memory Trick
A – Atomicity: All or Nothing
C – Consistency: Always follows database rules
I – Isolation: Transactions don't interfere with each other
D – Durability: Committed data is permanently stored
C = Correct rules
I = Independent execution
D = Data saved forever


"A Composite Key is a key formed by combining two or more columns to uniquely identify each record in a table."

👉 A single column is not enough to identify a row uniquely, so we combine multiple columns.

Example
Student_Course
student_id	course_id	grade
101	C101	A
101	C102	B
102	C101	A

Here,

student_id ❌ is not unique (101 appears twice)
course_id ❌ is not unique (C101 appears twice)

But together:

(student_id, course_id)

becomes:

student_id	course_id
101	C101 ✅
101	C102 ✅
102	C101 ✅

Every combination is unique.

So,

Composite Key = (student_id, course_id)

2,Candidate Key
"A Candidate Key is a column or combination of columns that can uniquely identify each record in a table. A table can have multiple candidate keys, and one of the
m is selected as the Primary Key."
Imagine you are a college principal.

There are 3 ways to identify a student:

Roll No	Email	Aadhaar
101	a@gmail.com	1234
102	b@gmail.com	5678
103	c@gmail.com	9999

Now I ask you:

Can Roll No identify a student uniquely?

✅ Yes.

Can Email identify a student uniquely?

✅ Yes.

Can Aadhaar identify a student uniquely?

✅ Yes.

So there are 3 columns that can uniquely identify a student.

These are called Candidate Keys.
But the database needs only ONE Primary Key.

Suppose we choose:

Roll No

Then:

✅ Roll No → Primary Key
✅ Email → Candidate Key (not chosen)
✅ Aadhaar → Candidate Key (not chosen)


